Date: Tue 1 Sep 2020
From: Dr. T. Jacob John [edited]


Re: ProMED-mail post Japanese encephalitis & other - India (12): (BR) 20200831.7730992
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
You seem to have misunderstood the news item published in Devdiscourse, Asian News International.

The 9 deaths reported is the season's total (compared with more than 200 last year, 2019). This 9 includes the 6 and 2 cases that you refer to in the text, with appropriate news media references. Of these 9, 2 were from neighboring districts (Vaishali and East Champaran) and 7 from Muzaffarpur district, within which is the city with the same name, where the SKMS Medical College Hospital is located.

It is clearly mentioned in one newspaper report that for one child the doctor did not give the recommended correct treatment of 10% dextrose, and later the child died. Now, the recommended treatment of 10% dextrose is for "hypoglycemic encephalopathy," which is the annually recurring "AES" in Muzaffarpur district (see Sarkar A, Datta D, Datta SK, John TJ. Acute encephalopathy in children in Muzaffarpur, India: a review of aetiopathogenesis. Trans R Soc Trop Med Hyg. 2020; 114: 704-11. https://doi.org/10.1093/trstmh/traa036).

Hypoglycemic encephalopathy is triggered by litchi consumption, and Muzaffarpur, Vaishali, East Champaran and Sitamarhi are litchi-growing districts in Bihar.

These 4 are non-Japanese encephalitis districts.

--
